 actors in Malayalam cinema]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian male actors]]\n[[Category:Best Child Artist National Film Award winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Tarun jhala\n| image              = https://images.app.goo.gl/cHmB1M3e77eqvaHLA\n| birth_name         = Tarun\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|2000|08|07}}\n| birth_place        = [[Jodhpur]], [[rajasthan]], India\n| occupation         = Actor\n| yearsactive        = 1990\u2013present\n| parents            = Pushpa devi(mother)<br/>mahendra jhala(father)\n}}\n'''Tarun Kumar''' is an [[Indian film]] actor known for his works predominantly in [[Telugu cinema]]. He has also appeared in few [[Tamil language|Tamil]] and [[Malayalam cinema|Malayalam]] films. He has received three state [[Nandi Awards]] and the [[National Film Awards|National Film Award]] for his works.<ref>{{cite news|author=maatv |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=d8-mVkwPo-Y |title=Tarun Birthday Special |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=2012-09-19}}</ref> His famous line \"You're a Dora bell \" is now iconic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0850761/bio|title=Tarun|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref>\n\nHe received the [[National Film Award for Best Child Artist]] in 1991, for his work in [[Mani Ratnam]]'s ''[[Anjali (1990 film)|Anjali]]'', which was [[List of Indian submissions for the Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film|India's official entry to the Oscars]] for that year.<ref name=\"38thawardPDF\">{{cite web|url=http://dff.nic.in/2011/38th_nff_1991.pdf|title=38th National Film Awards|format=PDF|publisher=[[Directorate of Film Festivals]]|accessdate=9 January 2012}}</ref> Tarun won critical acclaim with the Malayalam children's film, ''[[Abhayam (1991 film)|Abhayam]]'' (1991), which won the [[National Film Award for Best Children's Film]] for that year, and Tarun won the Best Child artist Award at the ''Furoshiki Film Festival in Japan''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/thehindu/mp/2004/02/05/stories/2004020500310100.htm|title=The Hindu : Chocolate HERO|work=thehindu.com}}</ref> As a child artist, Tarun starred in super hits such as ''Manasu Mamatha'' (1990), ''[[Surya IPS]]'' (1991), ''[[Aditya 369]]'' (1991),  ''[[Teja (film)|Teja]]'' (1992), ''[[My Dear Muthachan]]'' (1992), and ''[[Johny (film)|Johny]]'' (1993).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://entertainment.oneindia.in/telugu/reviews/nava-vasantham-review-261107.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721180508/http://entertainment.oneindia.in/telugu/reviews/nava-vasantham-review-261107.html|title=Nava Vasantham - Review|archivedate=21 July 2011|work=oneindia.in}}</ref>\n\nAfter a seven-year break, Tarun was the lead actor in the [[blockbuster (entertainment)|blockbuster]] ''[[Nuvve Kavali]]'' in 2000, which won the [[National Film Award for Best Feature Film in Telugu]] for that year, and Tarun won the [[Filmfare Award for Best Male Debut \u2013 South]] for his work in the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://awardsandwinners.com/category/filmfare-awards-south/2001/|title=Filmfare Awards South - 2001 - Winners & Nominees|work=awardsandwinners.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://kretyanews.com/nava-vasantham-telugu-movie.html |title=kretyanews Nava Vasantham Movie|work=kretyanews.com}}</ref> He then starred in successful films such as ''[[Priyamaina Neeku]]'' (2001), ''[[Nuvvu leka nenu lenu|Nuvvu Leka Nenu Lenu]]'' (2002), ''[[Nuvve Nuvve]]'' (2002), ''[[Punnagai Desam]]'' (2002) (Tamil), ''[[Ninne Istapaddanu]]'' (2003), ''[[Ela Cheppanu]]'' (2003), ''[[Nee Manasu Naaku Telusu]]'' (2003), ''[[Sakhiya]]'' (2004), ''[[Bhale Dongalu]]'' (2008), ''[[Sasirekha Parinayam (film)|Sasirekha Parinayam]]'' (2009), ''[[Chukkalanti Ammayi Chakkanaina Abbayi]]'' (2013), ''[[Yuddham]]'' (2014), and ''Idhi Naa Love Story'' (2018), and established himself as one of the successful actors of Telugu cinema.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kretyanews.com/nava-vasantham-telugu-movie.html |title=kretyanews Nava Vasantham Movie|work=kretyanews.com}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nTarun is the  child of  S. Chakrapani  and actress [[Roja Ramani]]. He started his acting career at the age of eight, under [[Ushakiran Movies]] production, before going on to win the National Film Award for Best Child Artist for his performance in [[Mani Ratnam]]'s Tamil film, ''[[Anjali (1990 film)|Anjali]]'' in 1990, alongside his co-stars [[Shamili]] and Shruti. Tarun took a seven-year break from appearing in films to complete his education, though he appeared in television commercials shot by [[Rajiv Menon]].\n\n==Non-film work==\nTarun is an accomplished [[cricketer]] and participates in Indian [[Celebrity Cricket League]]. He is the brand ambassador of Medak Mavericks team of Telangana T20 League cricket.\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:95%;\"\n|-  style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! Year !! Film !! Role !! Language !! Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |1990 || ''Manasu Mamatha'' || ||rowspan=\"2\" | Telugu ||[[Nandi Award for Best Child Actor]]\n|-\n| ''Bujjigadi Babai'' || || \n|-\n| ''[[Anjali (1990 film)|Anjali]]'' || Arjun  ||rowspan=\"2\" | Tamil || [[National Film Award for Best Child Artist]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" |1991 || ''[[Thalapathi]]'' || Petty thief || [[Cameo appearance]]\n|-\n| ''[[Surya IPS]]'' || ||rowspan=\"2\" | Telugu ||\n|-\n| ''[[Pillalu Diddina Kapuram]]'' || || [[Nandi Award for Best Child Actor]]\n|-\n| ''[[Abhayam (1991 film)|Abhayam]]'' || Vinu || Malayalam ||Best Child Artist Award - ''Furoshiki Film Festival in Japan''\n|-\n| ''[[Aditya 369]]'' || Kishore Kumar || Telugu ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |1992 || ''[[Meera (1992 film)|Meera]]'' || Jesu || Tamil || \n|-\n| ''[[Teja (film)|Teja]]'' || Teja || Telugu ||[[Nandi Award for Best Child Actor]]\n|-\n| ''[[My Dear Muthachan]]'' ||