 Hyderabad, India]]\n[[Category:Indian male child actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors in Telugu cinema]]\n[[Category:Indian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors in Malayalam cinema]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian male actors]]\n[[Category:Best Child Artist National Film Award winners]]\n", "name_user": "Tarun jhala", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tarun_Kumar"}
{"title_page": "European Project on Ocean Acidification", "text_new": "[[File:Epoca.png|thumb|alt=|logo]]\nThe '''European Project on Ocean Acidification''' ('''EPOCA''') was Europe's first major research initiative and the first large-scale international research effort devoted to studying the impacts and consequences of [[ocean acidification]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cordis.europa.eu/project/rcn/87798/factsheet/en|title=CORDIS {{!}} European Commission|website=cordis.europa.eu|access-date=2019-01-11}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite journal | last1 = Gattuso | first1 = J.-P. | last2 = Hansson | first2 = L. | year = 2009 | title = European Project on Ocean Acidification (EPOCA): Objectives, products, and scientific highlights | url = https://doi.org/10.5670/oceanog.2009.108 | journal = Oceanography | volume = 22 | issue = 4| pages = 190\u2013201 | doi = 10.5670/oceanog.2009.108 }}</ref> EPOCA was an EU [[Framework Programmes for Research and Technological Development|FP7 Integrated Project]] active during four years, from 2008 to 2012.\n\nThe EPOCA consortium brought together more than 160 researchers from 32 institutes in 10 European countries (Belgium, France, Germany, Iceland, Italy, The Netherlands, Norway, Sweden, Switzerland, and the United Kingdom) and was coordinated by the [[Centre national de la recherche scientifique|French Centre National de la Recherche Scientifique (CNRS)]] with the project office based at the Institut de la Mer de Villefranche, France (formerly [[Observatoire Oceanologique de Villefranche|Observatoire Oc\u00e9anologique de Villefranche]]).<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Scope ==\nThe research carried out through EPOCA was structured around four themes :\n\n# Theme 1 investigated the changes in ocean chemistry and [[biogeography]] across space and time. Paleo-reconstruction methods were used on several archives, including [[foraminifera]] and deep-sea corals, to determine the past variability in ocean chemistry and to tie these to present-day chemical and biological observations;\n# Theme 2 studied the sensitivity of marine organisms, communities and [[ecosystem]]s to ocean acidification.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           Key climate-relevant [[Biogeochemistry|biogeochemical]] processes such as [[calcification]], [[primary production]] and [[nitrogen fixation]] were investigated using a large array of techniques, ranging from molecular tools to physiological and ecological approaches.                                                 Perturbation experiments were carried out both in the laboratory and in the field, including a major large-scale offshore [[mesocosm]] experiment in Svalbard in 2010 <ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=|title=Arctic ocean acidification: pelagic ecosystem and biogeochemical responses during a mesocosm study.|url=https://www.biogeosciences.net/special_issue120.html|journal=Biogeosciences|issue=Special Issue|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n# Theme 3 focused on the integration of the results from Themes 1 and 2 in biogeochemical, [[sediment]], and coupled ocean-climate models to better understand and project the responses of the Earth system to ocean acidification.                                                                                      Special attention was paid to feedbacks of physiological changes on the carbon, nitrogen, sulfur and iron cycles and how these changes will affect and be affected by future [[climate change]];\n# Finally, Theme 4 synthesized the results from Themes 1-3 and assessed uncertainties, risks and thresholds (\"tipping points\") related to ocean acidification at scales ranging from subcellular to ecosystem and local to global scales.                                                                 A second focus of this theme was to communicate the findings to fellow scientists but also to policy makers, media, schools and the general public.\n\n== Legacy ==\nEPOCA significantly contributed to advancing the state of knowledge on ocean acidification and its impact on [[Marine life|marine organisms]] and ecosystems. The project produced more than 200 research articles, equivalent to 20% of the [[Peer review|peer-reviewed]] scientific literature on ocean acidification published during the period 2009-2012.<ref name=\":1\">OA-ICC Bibliographic database on ocean acidification https://www.iaea.org/services/oa-icc/science-and-collaboration/data-access-and-management</ref><ref name=\":2\">Data compilation on the biological response to ocean acidification https://www.pangaea.de/?f.project=EPOCA</ref>\n\nEPOCA leaves behind products still widely used by the international scientific community working on ocean acidification, such as :\n\n* EPOCA scientists designed and developed the [[R (programming language)|R software]] package seacarb, which calculates parameters of the seawater carbonate system and includes functions useful for ocean acidification research;<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gattuso|first=J.-P.|last2=Lavigne|first2=H.|last3=Hansson|first3=L.|title=Technical Note: Approaches and software tools to investigate the impact of ocean acidification.|url=https://www.biogeosciences.net/6/2121/2009/bg-6-2121-2009.html|journal=Biogeosciences|volume=6|issue=10|pages=2121\u20132133|via=|doi=10.5194/bg-6-2121-2009|year=2009|bibcode=2009BGeo....6.2121G}}</ref><ref>R package seacarb https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/seacarb/index.html</ref>\n* EPOCA led the production of the community-reviewed \u201c''<u>Guide to best practices in ocean acidification research and data reporting</u>''\u201d, published in 2010 as a collaborative effort of EPOCA and international colleagues to provide guidance on design of ocean acidification experiments and to facilitate comparisons of studies <ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.iaea.org/sites/default/files/18/06/oa-guide-to-best-practices.pdf|title=Guide to best practices for ocean acidification research and data reporting.|last=Riebesell|first=U.|last2=Fabry|first2=V. J.|last3=Hansson|first3=L.|last4=Gattuso|first4=J.-P.|publisher=Publications Office of the European Union|year=2010|isbn=|location=Luxembourg|pages=}}</ref> and;\n* EPOCA maintained and pioneered several resources made available to the international ocean acidification research community :                                                                                                                          \n** a news stream on ocean acidification launched in 2006 by Jean-Pierre Gattuso, which provides daily information on the latest scientific articles, media coverage, meetings, and job and training opportunities;<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news-oceanacidification-icc.org/|title=Ocean Acidification news stream|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=|publisher=Ocean Acidification International Coordination Centre (OA-ICC)}}</ref>       \n** a bibliographic database including research articles, books and book chapters with allocated keywords, launched in 1995 by Jean-Pierre Gattuso <ref name=\":1\" /> and;      \n** a compilation of data from peer-reviewed studies investigating a biological response to ocean acidification.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yang|first=Y.|last2=Hansson|first2=L.|last3=Gattuso|first3=J.-P.|date=2016|title=Data compilation on the biological response to ocean acidification : an update.|journal=Earth System Science Data|volume=8|issue=1|pages=79\u201387|doi=10.5194/essd-8-79-2016|bibcode=2016ESSD....8...79Y}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nisumaa|first=A.-M.|last2=Pesant|first2=S.|last3=Bellerby|first3=R. G. J.|last4=Delille|first4=B.|last5=Middelburg|first5=J. J.|last6=Orr|first6=J. C.|last7=Riebesell|first7=U.|last8=Tyrrell|first8=T.|last9=Wolf-Gladrow|first9=D.|last10=Gattuso|first10=J.-P.|date=2010|title=EPOCA/EUR-OCEANS data compilation on the biological and biogeochemical responses to ocean acidification.|url=https://www.earth-syst-sci-data.net/2/167/2010/essd-2-167-2010.html|journal=Earth System Science Data|volume=2|issue=2|pages=167\u2013175|via=|doi=10.5194/essd-2-167-2010|bibcode=2010ESSD....2..167N}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n\n* {{cite web|title=SOLAS IMBER Working Group on Ocean Acidification|url=http://www.imber.info/science/working-groups-1/solas-imber-carbon-sic/subgroup-3-ocean-acidification-sioa-1}}\n* {{cite web|title=IAEA Ocean Acidification International Coordination Centre (OA-ICC)|url=https://www.iaea.org/services/oa-icc|date=2018-02-05}}\n* {{cite web|title=Ocean Acidification news stream|url=https://news-oceanacidification-icc.org/|date=}}\n* {{cite web|title=OA-ICC Bibliographic database|url=https://www.iaea.org/services/oa-icc/science-and-collaboration/data-access-and-management|date=2018-02-07}}\n* {{cite web|title=Data compilation on the biological response to ocean acidification|url=http://oa-icc.ipsl.fr/}}\n\n[[Category:Oceanography]]\n[[Category:Marine biology]]\n[[Category:Climate institutions and programs]]\n[[Category:Climate change]]\n[[Category:Global warming]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Epoca.png|thumb|alt=|logo]]\nThe '''European Project on Ocean Acidification''' ('''EPOCA''') was Europe's first major research initiative and the first large-scale international research effort devoted to studying the impacts and consequences of [[ocean acidification]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cordis.europa.eu/project/rcn/87798/factsheet/en|title=CORDIS {{!}} European Commission|website=cordis.europa.eu|access-date=2019-01-11}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">Gattuso J.-P., Hansson L. & the EPOCA Consortium, 2009. European Project on Ocean Acidification (EPOCA): Objectives, products, and scientific highlights. ''Oceanography'' 22(4): 190\u2013201 https://doi.org/10.5670/oceanog.2009.108</ref> EPOCA was an EU [[Framework Programmes for Research and Technological Development|FP7 Integrated Project]] active during four years, from 2008 to 2012.\n\nThe EPOCA consortium brought together more than 160 researchers from 32 institutes in 10 European countries (Belgium, France, Germany, Iceland, Italy, The Netherlands, Norway, Sweden, Switzerland, and the United Kingdom) and was coordinated by the [[Centre national de la recherche scientifique|French Centre National de la Recherche Scientifique (CNRS)]] with the project office based at the Institut de la Mer de Villefranche, France (formerly [[Observatoire Oceanologique de Villefranche|Observatoire Oc\u00e9anologique de Villefranche]]).<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Scope ==\nThe research carried out through EPOCA was structured around four themes :\n\n# Theme 1 investigated the changes in ocean chemistry and [[biogeography]] across space and time. Paleo-reconstruction methods were used on several archives, including [[foraminifera]] and deep-sea corals, to determine the past variability in ocean chemistry and to tie these to present-day chemical and biological observations;\n# Theme 2 studied the sensitivity of marine organisms, communities and [[ecosystem]]s to ocean acidification.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           Key climate-relevant [[Biogeochemistry|biogeochemical]] processes such as [[calcification]], [[primary production]] and [[nitrogen fixation]] were investigated using a large array of techniques, ranging from molecular tools to physiological and ecological approaches.                                                 Perturbation experiments were carried out both in the laboratory and in the field, including a major large-scale offshore [[mesocosm]] experiment in Svalbard in 2010 <ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=|title=Arctic ocean acidification: pelagic ecosystem and biogeochemical responses during a mesocosm study.|url=https://www.biogeosciences.net/special_issue120.html|journal=Biogeosciences|issue=Special Issue|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n# Theme 3 focused on the integration of the results from Themes 1 and 2 in biogeochemical, [[sediment]], and coupled ocean-climate models to better understand and project the responses of the Earth system to ocean acidification.                                                                                      Special attention was paid to feedbacks of physiological changes on the carbon, nitrogen, sulfur and iron cycles and how these changes will affect and be affected by future [[climate change]];\n# Finally, Theme 4 synthesized the results from Themes 1-3 and assessed uncertainties, risks and thresholds (\"tipping points\") related to ocean acidification at scales ranging from subcellular to ecosystem and local to global scales.                                                                 A second focus of this theme was to communicate the findings to fellow scientists but also to policy makers, media, schools and the general public.\n\n== Legacy ==\nEPOCA significantly contributed to advancing the state of knowledge on ocean acidification and its impact on [[Marine life|marine organisms]] and ecosystems. The project produced more than 200 research articles, equivalent to 20% of the [[Peer review|peer-reviewed]] scientific literature on ocean acidification published during the period 2009-2012.<ref name=\":1\">OA-ICC Bibliographic database on ocean acidification https://www.iaea.org/services/oa-icc/science-and-collaboration/data-access-and-management</ref><ref name=\":2\">Data compilation on the biological response to ocean acidification https://www.pangaea.de/?f.project=EPOCA</ref>\n\nEPOCA leaves behind products still widely used by the international scientific community working on ocean acidification, such as :\n\n* EPOCA scientists designed and developed the [[R (programming language)|R software]] package seacarb, which calculates parameters of the seawater carbonate system and includes functions useful for ocean acidification research;<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gattuso|first=J.-P.|last2=Lavigne|first2=H.|last3=Hansson|first3=L.|title=Technical Note: Approaches and software tools to investigate the impact of ocean acidification.|url=https://www.biogeosciences.net/6/2121/2009/bg-6-2121-2009.html|journal=Biogeosciences|volume=6|issue=10|pages=2121\u20132133|via=|doi=10.5194/bg-6-2121-2009|year=2009|bibcode=2009BGeo....6.2121G}}</ref><ref>R package seacarb https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/seacarb/index.html</ref>\n* EPOCA led the production of the community-reviewed \u201c''<u>Guide to best practices in ocean acidification research and data reporting</u>''\u201d, published in 2010 as a collaborative effort of EPOCA and international colleagues to provide guidance on design of ocean acidification experiments and to facilitate comparisons of studies <ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.iaea.org/sites/default/files/18/06/oa-guide-to-best-practices.pdf|title=Guide to best practices for ocean acidification research and data reporting.|last=Riebesell|first=U.|last2=Fabry|first2=V. J.|last3=Hansson|first3=L.|last4=Gattuso|first4=J.-P.|publisher=Publications Office of the European Union|year=2010|isbn=|location=Luxembourg|pages=}}</ref> and;\n* EPOCA maintained and pioneered several resources made available to the international ocean acidification research community :                                                                                                                          \n** a news stream on ocean acidification launched in 2006 by Jean-Pierre Gattuso, which provides daily information on the latest scientific articles, media coverage, meetings, and job and training opportunities;<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news-oceanacidification-icc.org/|title=Ocean Acidification news stream|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=|publisher=Ocean Acidification International Coordination Centre (OA-ICC)}}</ref>       \n** a bibliographic database including research articles, books and book chapters with allocated keywords, launched in 1995 by Jean-Pierre Gattuso <ref name=\":1\" /> and;      \n** a compilation of data from peer-reviewed studies investigating a biological response to ocean acidification.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yang|first=Y.|last2=Hansson|first2=L.|last3=Gattuso|first3=J.-P.|date=2016|title=Data compilation on the biological response to ocean acidification : an update.|journal=Earth System Science Data|volume=8|issue=1|pages=79\u201387|doi=10.5194/essd-8-79-2016|bibcode=2016ESSD....8...79Y}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nisumaa|first=A.-M.|last2=Pesant|first2=S.|last3=Bellerby|first3=R. G. J.|last4=Delille|first4=B.|last5=Middelburg|first5=J. J.|last6=Orr|first6=J. C.|last7=Riebesell|first7=U.|last8=Tyrrell|first8=T.|last9=Wolf-Gladrow|first9=D.|last10=Gattuso|first10=J.-P.|date=2010|title=EPOCA/EUR-OCEANS data compilation on the biological and biogeochemical responses to ocean acidification.|url=https://www.earth-syst-sci-data.net/2/167/2010/essd-2-167-2010.html|journal=Earth System Science Data|volume=2|issue=2|pages=167\u2013175|via=|doi=10.5194/essd-2-167-2010|bibcode=2010ESSD....2..167N}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n\n* {{cite web|title=SOLAS IMBER Working Group on Ocean Acidification|url=http://www.imber.info/science/working-groups-1/solas-imber-carbon-sic/subgroup-3-ocean-acidification-sioa-1}}\n* {{cite web|title=IAEA Ocean Acidification International Coordination Centre (OA-ICC)|url=https://www.iaea.org/services/oa-icc|date=2018-02-05}}\n* {{cite web|title=Ocean Acidification news stream|url=https://news-oceanacidification-icc.org/|date=}}\n* {{cite web|title=OA-ICC Bibliographic database|url=https://www.iaea.org/services/oa-icc/science-and-collaboration/data-access-and-management|date=2018-02-07}}\n* {{cite web|title=Data compilation on the biological response to ocean acidification|url=http://oa-icc.ipsl.fr/}}\n\n[[Category:Oceanography]]\n[[Category:Marine biology]]\n[[Category:Climate institutions and programs]]\n[[Category:Climate change]]\n[[Category:Global warming]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Journal cites:, templated 1 journal cites", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/European_Project_on_Ocean_Acidification"}
{"title_page": "List of units and formations of the British Army 2020", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=March 2017}}\n\nThe [[British Army]] as a result of the [[Army 2020|Army 2020 Refine]] reforms are organised into two main commands, [[Commander Field Army|Field Army]] and [[Commander Home Command|Home Command]], each commanded by a [[Lieutenant-general (United Kingdom)|lieutenant general]].\n\n[[Permanent Joint Headquarters]] (PJHQ) plans and executes UK-led joint and multinational operations, including those involving British Army units, and operationally commands UK forces assigned to multinational operations led by other nation-states.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/groups/the-permanent-joint-headquarters|title=The Permanent Joint Headquarters|website=GOV.UK|language=en|access-date=2019-09-01}}</ref> For example, during [[Operation Telic]], the Chief of Joint Operations at PJHQ directed Major General [[Robin Brims]], the UK Land Contingent Commander, through the UK National Contingent Commander, [[Air Marshal]] [[Brian Burridge]].<ref>[http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20171123124640/http://www.iraqinquiry.org.uk/media/247900/the-report-of-the-iraq-inquiry_section-80.pdf The Report of the Iraqi Inquiry: The Invasion], pages 7 & 8, paragraphs 23, 25, 26.</ref>\n\nBritish Army forces may also be deployed to NATO operations, which then are delegated by [[North Atlantic Council]] or other NATO bodies to the [[Supreme Allied Commander Europe]] who delegates the operation to relevant headquarters. PJHQ may still be involved.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm199900/cmselect/cmdfence/347/34717.htm#note463 |title=Fourteenth Report: Lessons of Kosovo III THE CONDUCT OF THE CAMPAIGN:Command, Coordination and Intelligence  |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=23 October 2000 |website=publications.parliament.uk |publisher=Defence Select Committee |access-date=6 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{Wide image|UK Army 2018.png|4400px|Structure of the British Army 2018-19|550px|right}}\n\n== Field Army ==\n{{see also|Commander Field Army}}\nThe units under Field Army are:<ref name=\"aff\">[http://www.aff.org.uk/linkedfiles/aff/latest_news_information/cregulararmybasingannouncementgridunclas.pdf Regular Army basing matrix by formation and unit] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160814181412/http://www.aff.org.uk/linkedfiles/aff/latest_news_information/cregulararmybasingannouncementgridunclas.pdf |date=2016-08-14 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.army.mod.uk/documents/general/Army2020_Report.pdf Army 2020 Update] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140610215557/http://www.army.mod.uk/documents/general/Army2020_Report.pdf |date=June 10, 2014 }}</ref>\n* '''Reaction forces''' comprising [[16 Air Assault Brigade]] and 3rd (UK) Division of two armoured infantry brigades, the 12th and 20th Armoured Infantry Brigades, and two Strike brigades: 1st Strike Brigade and an as-yet-unnamed strike brigade, along with combat support units.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/defence/9911295/Famed-Desert-Rats-to-lose-their-tanks-under-Army-cuts.html|title=Famed Desert Rats to lose their tanks under Army cuts|work=Telegraph|date=2013-03-05|accessdate=2013-03-09|last1=Kirkup|first1=James}}</ref><ref>[https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/136406/regular_army_basing_plan.pdf Army Basing Plan: The basing plan table labels them as \"Armoured Infantry Brigades\"]</ref><ref name=\"Dec162\"/> 3rd UK Division is operationally affiliated with the [[Allied Rapid Reaction Corps]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://arrc.nato.int/about-us/formations |title=Assigned Formations |date= 31 January 2018 |website=arrc.nato.int |publisher=Allied Rapid Reaction Corps |access-date=6 September 2019}}</ref>\n* '''Adaptive forces''' comprising a 1st (UK) Division brigades, three of which (the 4th, 7th, and 51st) will be deployable.<ref>[https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/136406/regular_army_basing_plan.pdf Army Basing Plan: The basing plan table labels them in order]</ref><ref>[http://www.rfca-yorkshire.org.uk/files/TransformingtheBritishArmyAnnexA.pdf Transforming the British Army Annex A]{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>[http://www.rfca-yorkshire.org.uk/files/TransformingtheBritishArmyAnnexC.pdf Transforming the British Army Annex C]{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n* '''6th (UK) Division''' comprising surveillance, intelligence, reconnaissance, communications, electronic warfare, psychological operations.\n* '''Joint Helicopter Command''' which commands most of the UK's battlefield lift and attack helicopters for the Royal Navy, British Army and Royal Air Force.\n\nField Army gained initial operating capability on 30 November 2015 and was formed as a result of the  2015 Army Command Review. The Commander Field Army commands all the formations of the British Army's forces for operational tasks, its collective training and tactical doctrine organisations and includes the vast majority of the Army\u2019s fighting equipment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.army.mod.uk/news/28058.aspx |title=Flag raised to signal new HQ Field Army |date=23 November 2015 |accessdate=26 August 2019 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151124164925/http://www.army.mod.uk/news/28058.aspx |archivedate=24 November 2015 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n=== 1st (United Kingdom) Division ===\n* '''[[1st (United Kingdom) Division]]''',<ref name=\"Army 2019\">{{cite web |title=Army restructures to confront evolving threats |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/army-restructures-to-confront-evolving-threats |publisher=UK Government |accessdate=1 August 2019}}</ref> in [[York]] (Adaptable Force)\n\n==== 4th Infantry Brigade and Headquarters North East ====\n{{Location map+ | United Kingdom\n| width = 330\n| 